data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which gives poor failure messages (just "Assert.IsTrue failed"). MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.Contains(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"), users);
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Your code | Better alternative | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Shows "collection was empty" vs generic failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Shows "expected 3, found N" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` | Shows "value was null" |

The `users.All(u => u.IsActive)` check is one case where `Assert.IsTrue` is still reasonable — there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" method.

Also consider sealing your test class (`public sealed class ...`) for performance, per MSTest best practices.
